  "text": "In this part of the study, we applied the VP LBM to a curved boundary, by focusing on a flow between two cylinders, as shown in Figure 9 . The length and width of the square computational domain are L = 200 l.u., and the radii of the inner and the outer cylinders located in the center of the domain, are R 1 = 45 l.u. and R 2 = 70 l.u. respectively. While the outer cylinder is motionless (Ω 2 = 0), the inner cylinder moves according to the angular velocity Ω 1 = u d /R 1 . In the computations, u d was small enough to deal with a low Mach number flow (u d = 0.01 l.u.). This configuration was studied by [CITATION_1] and [CITATION_2] , who evaluated the immersed boundary method implemented in a lattice Boltzmann framework. For this case, the analytical profile of the tangential velocity component is:",
